WEBVTT

00:00:00.400 --> 00:00:06.000
Today I want to posit the following idea to you all, and that is most data scientists like us

00:00:07.040 --> 00:00:12.720
would benefit by thinking more end-to-end. And I'll make a case for why I believe that,

00:00:12.720 --> 00:00:18.240
and I'll also share some principles on how you can start thinking end-to-end and benefit your

00:00:18.240 --> 00:00:25.280
own organizations. And I want to start by defining what I mean by end-to-end, and that is bringing

00:00:25.280 --> 00:00:31.200
ideas to life. And so I think we already saw some compelling examples in this session,

00:00:32.400 --> 00:00:36.880
but I'll give another one, and that is at my company, How We Think End-to-End,

00:00:37.520 --> 00:00:43.599
at NMDP, our mission is to save lives through cell therapy. And I think like many of you,

00:00:44.240 --> 00:00:49.520
we come up with lots of ideas to advance the missions of our organization, and for us,

00:00:49.520 --> 00:00:54.720
that really means thinking about our patients and donors. Many of our patients have blood

00:00:54.720 --> 00:01:00.320
cancers like leukemia, and the best shot for cure is to find the perfectly matched donor.

00:01:01.360 --> 00:01:06.720
And there are many things that go into this matching, one of them being how ready our donors

00:01:06.720 --> 00:01:12.800
are, how likely they are to be available when called upon. Because unfortunately, for a variety

00:01:12.800 --> 00:01:18.480
of reasons, not all our donors will be available, and that can make a stressful situation for a

00:01:18.480 --> 00:01:22.720
searching patient even more stressful, as many of them don't have the luxury of time.

00:01:23.680 --> 00:01:29.839
So one of the ideas that we had, which just comes from a lot of conversation with both our internal

00:01:29.839 --> 00:01:35.279
and external partners, is can we predict how ready a donor is going to be for donation before they

00:01:35.279 --> 00:01:41.360
get called? And bringing this idea to life would mean providing this prediction and information to

00:01:41.360 --> 00:01:47.440
our physicians in real time, so that when they're talking to their patients every day, they can run

00:01:47.599 --> 00:01:55.919
a search and have the most informed decision for their patient. And so thinking end-to-end is really

00:01:55.919 --> 00:02:01.519
about going from this idea phase, from usually just a conversation, all the way to a final product

00:02:02.160 --> 00:02:05.599
that benefits the users who need the information the most.

00:02:07.919 --> 00:02:12.160
And so it's very challenging, especially when it's your first foray into a new

00:02:13.119 --> 00:02:19.679
kind of domain. For us, this was our first foray into machine learning. We wanted to build this

00:02:19.679 --> 00:02:24.479
new donor readiness score to provide this information to our transplant center physicians.

00:02:25.759 --> 00:02:31.119
And so on one end, at the start of the process, you have me, the developer, in a rapid ideation phase,

00:02:31.919 --> 00:02:38.160
just coming up with ideas, doing some exploratory data analyses, and getting a local prototype of

00:02:38.160 --> 00:02:43.679
this donor readiness score. But we also have to think about the other end, and that is our

00:02:43.679 --> 00:02:49.360
physician end-users in this case. They are most concerned about having this donor readiness score

00:02:49.360 --> 00:02:56.399
available to them in the medical system that they use, and they want to ensure that it's up-to-date,

00:02:56.399 --> 00:03:02.240
they can trust it, and we also want to protect our donor information. We want to protect their

00:03:02.240 --> 00:03:10.320
privacy. And so there's a big gap between going from prototype online laptop to something that's

00:03:10.320 --> 00:03:16.559
going to be useful to our hundreds of external network partners and end-users in the medical

00:03:16.559 --> 00:03:21.839
system and workflows that they use day-to-day. And I think this is a gap a lot of data scientists face

00:03:21.839 --> 00:03:26.880
of, how do you get your work into the hands of those that would benefit most from it?

00:03:27.839 --> 00:03:32.880
And I'll start by saying you definitely don't want to do this and say, it works on my machine,

00:03:32.880 --> 00:03:38.320
I'm good, we'll ship my machine to hundreds of different people, you might as well teach them

00:03:38.320 --> 00:03:43.119
R, Python, Docker, all that stuff while you're at it. It's not going to work.

00:03:45.039 --> 00:03:52.320
So what worked for us was to try to loop in other teams. And so here we start in our comfort zone

00:03:52.320 --> 00:03:58.320
of the business ideas, the developer, the data scientist, you and me. And I think this is a

00:03:58.320 --> 00:04:06.880
pretty comfortable workflow where we often get questions, we provide answers. And when it comes

00:04:06.880 --> 00:04:14.479
to these big new projects and trying to get buy-in from the entire organization, it becomes a little

00:04:14.479 --> 00:04:20.000
bit more daunting of, how do I make sure my thing is up-to-date every single day? It's going to be

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:26.799
sent to external clients. How do we make sure they trust what we're building for them? And that's when

00:04:27.600 --> 00:04:32.720
we typically think of our engineering teams and we try to loop them in because our data engineers

00:04:32.720 --> 00:04:40.000
are experts at building scalable data pipelines and protecting our donor information. Our DevOps

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:45.200
engineers are experts at scaling compute into the cloud, building the infrastructure that we need.

00:04:45.679 --> 00:04:48.959
And of course, our software engineers help build the applications

00:04:48.959 --> 00:04:53.279
that our transplant center partners can use and integrate into their workflows.

00:04:55.279 --> 00:05:00.320
So then the question becomes, how do you hand off from your comfort zone to this engineering

00:05:00.320 --> 00:05:04.720
zone? And it's actually really tricky because among these engineering zones, they don't

00:05:04.720 --> 00:05:09.920
necessarily work together all the time. They're not one cohesive unit, especially when we're

00:05:09.920 --> 00:05:14.880
introducing this new machine learning functionality. There's kind of many handoffs

00:05:14.880 --> 00:05:21.279
within that engineering zone. And so it's also really tough because I wasn't a data engineer.

00:05:21.279 --> 00:05:26.000
I wasn't a DevOps engineer. I don't really know what's going to benefit the most. I have some R

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:30.399
scripts, some Python scripts, some SQL scripts. I know what donor readiness score should look like.

00:05:30.399 --> 00:05:36.399
I know what goes into it and what goes out. And so initially, we just tried a nice handoff process

00:05:36.399 --> 00:05:40.959
of, here are the requirements. Here are how we're building donor readiness score locally.

00:05:40.959 --> 00:05:47.359
Can you help us deploy this in production, automate this, build a custom application to

00:05:47.359 --> 00:05:53.519
get this to the hand of the end users? And after several months of work, we eventually got a

00:05:53.519 --> 00:05:58.559
solution that was successful. Our partners were able to view this donor readiness score in their

00:05:58.559 --> 00:06:08.239
systems. And so you might be wondering, what's wrong with this approach? Or why can't you just

00:06:08.239 --> 00:06:12.799
hand off your data science work to other teams? And that's because nothing you build is ever going

00:06:12.799 --> 00:06:18.000
to be perfect, especially on the first iteration. And so there's always going to be things that you

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:22.559
want to improve, things you want to add, like improving donor readiness score because we know

00:06:22.559 --> 00:06:28.079
of this business process change. And this began really, really hard because the donor readiness

00:06:28.079 --> 00:06:34.720
score that we developed in our comfort zone looks completely different once translated through the

00:06:34.720 --> 00:06:40.239
engineering zone. Because to them, our model is a black box. And then within each of those data,

00:06:40.239 --> 00:06:45.440
the DevOps, the software handoffs, those are also kind of mini black boxes. And so it became really

00:06:45.440 --> 00:06:50.399
hard for me to make changes to donor readiness. And on the flip side, they didn't necessarily want

00:06:50.399 --> 00:06:55.119
to put such a big investment, get four teams together in a room with a product manager,

00:06:55.760 --> 00:07:01.200
and just meet to make a potentially small change of improving accuracy by two or three percent.

00:07:02.559 --> 00:07:06.880
And so we spent a long time trying to think about how we can overcome this and make the

00:07:06.880 --> 00:07:14.320
handoff more smooth. And after about a year of trial and error, we landed on a solution to break

00:07:14.320 --> 00:07:20.559
down these barriers and increase our comfort zone as data scientists and be more comfortable

00:07:21.359 --> 00:07:23.920
talking about more parts of the data science life cycle.

00:07:24.799 --> 00:07:29.119
And this isn't going to happen overnight. You know, there's no free lunch, except maybe at

00:07:29.119 --> 00:07:36.079
PositConf. But I would say that the benefits of expanding your comfort zone and the investment

00:07:36.079 --> 00:07:42.160
in that is going to pay off in the long run. And why do I think that? First, you'll have full

00:07:42.160 --> 00:07:47.920
context of the entire process. And this is extremely helpful because you have a bird's

00:07:47.920 --> 00:07:53.519
eye view of what's going on. I think it's really important to be able to pinpoint, hey,

00:07:54.559 --> 00:07:58.799
if there is some update to our donor, to understand how that flows in your database,

00:07:58.799 --> 00:08:04.000
how that flows to your model, how your model gets sent back to the people who are building it for.

00:08:05.279 --> 00:08:09.600
Because when issues come up, then you can kind of spot check a few cases and really identify

00:08:09.600 --> 00:08:13.920
where in the pipeline things are going wrong, especially when there's handoffs between four

00:08:13.920 --> 00:08:19.119
different payments. Secondly, adding new functionality becomes so much easier.

00:08:19.839 --> 00:08:24.880
Because if you can start to learn a little bit of engineering language and not even anything

00:08:24.880 --> 00:08:29.359
too serious, but just provide context for your requests and the features you want to build.

00:08:30.559 --> 00:08:36.719
I'm sure we get all the time asked questions from the business of, hey, I need this data in two days.

00:08:36.719 --> 00:08:40.719
I'm not going to tell you why I need it or what I'm going to do with it. And that kind of makes

00:08:40.719 --> 00:08:45.679
you roll your eyes. You wish you had that context that would make it easier for you to work with

00:08:45.679 --> 00:08:49.840
them to provide the solution that works. The similar thing here to our engineering teams.

00:08:49.840 --> 00:08:54.320
We want to give them enough context to be able to build the best solution that's agreeable among

00:08:54.320 --> 00:09:00.479
all parties. And finally, I want to stress that thinking end-to-end means that you're not alone.

00:09:01.200 --> 00:09:05.280
Sometimes people think, if I have to think end-to-end, that means I have to do everything

00:09:05.280 --> 00:09:12.400
from start to finish. I'm going to become one giant silo, just working alone. And I can guarantee

00:09:12.400 --> 00:09:16.640
you, you're not going to replace your DevOps engineers or your data engineers. They're still

00:09:16.640 --> 00:09:21.359
going to be there. But I would think that you would be working more closely together with them

00:09:21.359 --> 00:09:25.840
instead of filling out an IT request, waiting a couple of weeks. Hopefully it moves to the

00:09:25.840 --> 00:09:30.719
IT system. And then finally getting to talk to someone about what you're trying to do.

00:09:31.679 --> 00:09:36.559
And so you'll be able to work with them at multiple touch points in the entire process.

00:09:37.760 --> 00:09:41.919
And if these aren't good enough fundamental reasons for you, a practical one is that

00:09:41.919 --> 00:09:46.080
you're going to kind of be forced to think end-to-end anyhow. I'm sure many of you have

00:09:46.080 --> 00:09:51.039
gotten an email like this of, Adam, I noticed that donor readiness score is not populating

00:09:51.039 --> 00:09:57.200
correctly in my application UI, whatever that means. Can you look into it? And again, if you

00:09:57.359 --> 00:10:03.280
have this kind of disjointed structure, this is also really easy to just make you roll your eyes

00:10:03.280 --> 00:10:09.039
and complain and be like, I don't build applications like a software engineer. Let me

00:10:09.039 --> 00:10:12.799
talk to my software developers. But they're probably going to be like, well, we haven't

00:10:12.799 --> 00:10:18.799
made any release updates. There's probably some compute that's going wrong in the DevOps process.

00:10:18.799 --> 00:10:22.159
And then they might point fingers back at the engineers and you're just kind of on a wild

00:10:23.119 --> 00:10:29.039
goose chase. And so if you're able to, again, think about how data flows from

00:10:29.760 --> 00:10:32.880
update to your donor, to database, to your model, to your prediction,

00:10:33.679 --> 00:10:38.799
it's really easy to identify where in that process something has gone wrong.

00:10:38.799 --> 00:10:44.000
And when you've done your homework and you can kind of build your case, provide some context,

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:47.599
show what you've done, show why you think it's this way, you're going to have a more

00:10:48.400 --> 00:10:55.840
receptive audience, in this case, our DevOps team. And so this is based on a true story.

00:10:57.520 --> 00:11:02.000
And I want to encourage you to not think of these emails as something that is terrible.

00:11:02.799 --> 00:11:06.880
In fact, I think it's kind of a good thing, because it means that the business stakeholders

00:11:06.880 --> 00:11:14.080
here, they value your work. They clearly also want to advance your mission of your company

00:11:14.080 --> 00:11:18.239
by making sure that this thing works, and they trust you to know how to resolve it.

00:11:19.119 --> 00:11:22.159
And because of that trust, I would encourage you to actually use

00:11:23.119 --> 00:11:28.000
these emails, these issues that come up, as an opportunity to start thinking end-to-end,

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:32.400
because you have a great reason to try to figure out what's going on with your

00:11:32.400 --> 00:11:35.599
donor readiness score pipeline, your model pipeline, your application pipeline.

00:11:37.119 --> 00:11:42.719
And so I'll go into example of what doing end-to-end work can look like.

00:11:43.200 --> 00:11:47.599
In this case, I talked with my DevOps team, and after we figured out this issue, we were like,

00:11:47.599 --> 00:11:51.760
wouldn't it be awesome if, instead of getting an email from a stakeholder,

00:11:51.760 --> 00:11:54.080
we could email ourselves and catch this in advance?

00:11:55.520 --> 00:12:00.080
And so this is something that sounds like a great idea of implementing email alerts.

00:12:00.080 --> 00:12:05.840
And starting in the traditional data science realm, it is overall pretty simple. We have this

00:12:05.840 --> 00:12:11.359
store.py module, which essentially makes a prediction based on an event, usually data

00:12:11.359 --> 00:12:16.640
coming in, and we get our score. And then we have some logic based on what we know of potential

00:12:16.640 --> 00:12:22.000
errors that have happened in the past. If that prediction fails, we send an email with some

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:26.799
useful message, and we can catch other errors, too. Nothing too crazy, pretty typical code that

00:12:26.799 --> 00:12:31.440
we would work with. But once you start asking questions about, you know, Adam, what does this

00:12:31.440 --> 00:12:36.719
send email function look like? Because don't we have to send emails from our AWS server to our

00:12:36.799 --> 00:12:42.559
internal NMDP email server? As a data scientist, that's not something you would typically think

00:12:42.559 --> 00:12:47.119
about, but definitely is something you would need to, in this case, to get your alerts to work

00:12:47.119 --> 00:12:53.679
properly. But don't panic, because remember, you're not alone. This is a great opportunity

00:12:53.679 --> 00:12:58.960
to work with your DevOps team, and instead of asking them to, hey, go do this for me, go fix

00:12:58.960 --> 00:13:05.280
this, if you ask them how to implement something, they'll be much more receptive, because it shows

00:13:05.280 --> 00:13:09.760
that you care, and potentially, if you know how to do this, the next thing we build, or if we

00:13:09.760 --> 00:13:13.760
improve donor readiness score, maybe this is something that we could do that would save them

00:13:13.760 --> 00:13:19.599
resources as well, and then you're expanding your skill set as a data scientist. Because from the

00:13:19.599 --> 00:13:26.239
DevOps lens, the equivalent codes and bits to them actually look really easy as well. So here we have

00:13:26.239 --> 00:13:33.119
a simple notification service in AWS, SNS, and we have some Terraform code, .tf, which essentially

00:13:33.119 --> 00:13:38.960
builds the resources we need in our AWS infrastructure to send emails. And there's a bunch

00:13:38.960 --> 00:13:44.559
of boilerplate code that's simple to most DevOps engineers. You create this SNS module, and the

00:13:44.559 --> 00:13:48.719
main thing that they'll probably point out to you is, hey, the custom thing here is we're building

00:13:48.719 --> 00:13:55.200
your resource that subscribes to email alerts. And if I wanted to change this email, maybe I'm doing

00:13:55.200 --> 00:14:01.200
some testing, and I expect some errors to come out, I don't have to go through the IT process

00:14:01.280 --> 00:14:06.960
of requesting a change or review, wait a few weeks just to test a few simple changes. I can just go

00:14:06.960 --> 00:14:13.520
in here, change my endpoint from production data alert at nmdp.org to my personal email.

00:14:15.119 --> 00:14:20.239
And if I ever have to build another machine learning model, which we want to do, we want

00:14:20.239 --> 00:14:28.640
to keep the momentum going, I can now implement my own email alert. And I understand that it's

00:14:28.640 --> 00:14:33.919
still pretty intimidating to dive into a new field, especially sometimes DevOps engineering,

00:14:33.919 --> 00:14:40.000
data engineering, which you don't have training in. But I would empower you to actually use your

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:44.880
data science skills and bring them with you. They're a really powerful tool set. And I want

00:14:44.880 --> 00:14:49.599
to illustrate that with this other example we have, where we have a Connect server that runs

00:14:49.599 --> 00:14:54.159
a bunch of automated reports, including some monitoring for our donor readiness score model.

00:14:55.119 --> 00:15:01.440
And one week, we started noticing a bunch of random failures across our 30, 40 reports,

00:15:02.640 --> 00:15:07.039
with some kind of obtuse log error messages. And we weren't really sure what was going on,

00:15:07.039 --> 00:15:12.479
so we thought it wouldn't hurt to reach out to our DevOps team. And the first thing that they

00:15:12.479 --> 00:15:17.119
came back with, which is actually pretty reasonable, is, well, there's been no infrastructure change

00:15:17.119 --> 00:15:22.159
that we know of. Are you sure it's not a Connect issue? Maybe it's a code issue with your R code.

00:15:22.159 --> 00:15:26.880
Maybe you have too many reports now running at the same time, and that's causing resource conflicts.

00:15:28.640 --> 00:15:33.599
And so these are definitely valid issues. And if you can eliminate potential issues,

00:15:33.599 --> 00:15:36.960
potential reasons, it's going to be much, much easier to troubleshoot that.

00:15:37.599 --> 00:15:45.039
And so all we needed to do, with some help, is look at this log messages file on our Linux server

00:15:45.039 --> 00:15:50.799
hosting our Connect instance. And it contains hundreds of thousands of lines of mostly gibberish,

00:15:50.799 --> 00:15:55.039
but a few nice things. For example, a timestamp of when an event happened.

00:15:55.599 --> 00:16:00.000
And in this case, the success was no. There was some error for whatever reason.

00:16:00.960 --> 00:16:04.799
And so my first instinct as a data scientist is, let me just scrape these logs,

00:16:05.760 --> 00:16:09.440
scrape them all for the timestamps when there's a success equals no, and just see

00:16:10.080 --> 00:16:16.080
when they're happening. And so here, there's about 10,000 error messages plotted. Each vertical line

00:16:16.080 --> 00:16:21.200
corresponds to the timestamp when there is a success equals no message. So maybe not too

00:16:21.200 --> 00:16:27.599
helpful yet, but then we combine this with the known timestamps when we had random failures,

00:16:28.400 --> 00:16:35.520
we overlay them, and we have perfect correlation. And so just with a few simple finding some data

00:16:35.520 --> 00:16:41.599
and plotting it, we're able to provide a really compelling case for probably something that's

00:16:41.599 --> 00:16:46.799
going on under the server. And our DevOps team was like, okay, let me reach out to our security

00:16:46.799 --> 00:16:52.000
team. Turns out there was a security scan every 30 minutes, but there was an expired certificate,

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:55.760
and it would just yell for a bunch, which would cause some downstream effects,

00:16:55.760 --> 00:17:00.159
like our Connect reports failing at random times. Seemingly random.

00:17:03.039 --> 00:17:06.319
And so I hope the idea I posited at the beginning of this session,

00:17:07.199 --> 00:17:13.760
I think in turn will increase your impact, has resonated with some of you, and you can start to

00:17:13.760 --> 00:17:19.280
think about how thinking broader picture and more aspects of the data science lifecycle will benefit

00:17:19.280 --> 00:17:23.680
you and your organization. And if you're really trying just to get started and you want to take

00:17:23.680 --> 00:17:28.800
away one message, the next time you get an email about, hey, there's this potential issue,

00:17:30.079 --> 00:17:33.920
try to lead the resolution of it. It doesn't mean you have to solve everything by yourself,

00:17:33.920 --> 00:17:37.920
but try to take an active role and learn a little bit more, adapt your tool set,

00:17:38.560 --> 00:17:43.040
adapt your skill set, because it's going to happen again, and it'll make next time even easier.

00:17:44.239 --> 00:17:49.119
And just one little piece of encouragement. If you can learn how neural networks move data around,

00:17:49.119 --> 00:17:53.359
maybe like causal inference and DAGs, I'm extremely confident that you can learn how

00:17:53.359 --> 00:18:01.280
data moves around from your IT system. And so with that, thank you. If you want to view my slides,

00:18:01.280 --> 00:18:04.160
they're on my GitHub. And if you want to connect with me on LinkedIn,

00:18:04.160 --> 00:18:08.160
please do. Happy to take questions whenever. Appreciate your time.

00:18:13.839 --> 00:18:19.839
Right. I think we have a couple of questions. First one is, how did you go about selecting

00:18:19.839 --> 00:18:25.760
the criteria for donor readiness? Any tips for selecting criteria for building a metric for

00:18:25.760 --> 00:18:34.000
something that seems qualitative? Yes. Awesome question. So we kind of did the

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:40.319
scan the ether approach, just talking to all the different business parties and stakeholders and

00:18:40.319 --> 00:18:46.239
operational processes that are involved and figuring out and trying to link what do we find

00:18:46.800 --> 00:18:51.119
is correlated with donor readiness, like likelihood to be available and called. We have a bunch of

00:18:51.119 --> 00:18:56.719
historical data from calling donors and seeing which ones are available. And we also have a

00:18:56.719 --> 00:19:03.040
great marketing team that tries to keep our donors engaged. And we have some communications,

00:19:03.040 --> 00:19:07.119
some campaigns to really keep the engagement up. And those all play an important role in

00:19:07.119 --> 00:19:12.079
our donor readiness score. All right. I actually think that's

00:19:12.079 --> 00:19:16.800
the only question we have time for. So we'll give Adam another round of applause. Thank you for his

00:19:16.800 --> 00:19:18.959
time.

